SIMPLE: new
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: New
<hw>New</hw> <pr>(n⟦umac⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Newer</adjf>
<pr>(n⟦umac⟧"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Newest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. OE. <ets>newe</ets>, AS.
<ets>niwe</ets>, <ets>neowe</ets>; akin to D. <ets>nieuw</ets>, OS.
<ets>niwi</ets>, OHG. <ets>niuwi</ets>, G. <ets>neu</ets>, Icel.
<ets>n⟦ymac⟧r</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>ny</ets>, Goth. <ets>niujis</ets>,
Lith. <ets>naujas</ets>, Russ. <ets>novuii</ets>, Ir. <ets>nua</ets>,
<ets>nuadh</ets>, Gael. <ets>nuadh</ets>, W. <ets>newydd</ets>, Armor.
<ets>nevez</ets>, L. <ets>novus</ets>, Gr. <grk>ne`os</grk>, Skr.
<ets>nava</ets>, and prob. to E. <ets>now</ets>. ⟦root⟧263. See
<er>Now</er>, and cf. <er>Announce</er>, <er>Innovate</er>,
<er>Neophyte</er>, <er>Novel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having
existed, or having been made, but a short time; having originated or
occurred lately; having recently come into existence, or into one's
possession; not early or long in being; of late origin; recent; fresh;
modern; -- opposed to <ant>old</ant>, <as>as, a <ex>new</ex> coat; a
<ex>new</ex> house; a <ex>new</ex> book; a <ex>new</ex>
fashion.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Your <xex>new</xex> wife.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not before seen or known, although existing before;
lately manifested; recently discovered; <as>as, a <ex>new</ex> metal; a
<ex>new</ex> planet; <ex>new</ex> scenes.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Newly beginning or recurring; starting anew; now
commencing; different from what has been; <as>as, a <ex>new</ex> year; a
<ex>new course</ex> or direction.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>As if lately begun or made; having the state or
quality of original freshness; also, changed for the better; renovated;
unworn; untried; unspent; <as>as, rest and travel made him a
<ex>new</ex> man</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Steadfasty purposing to lead a <qex>new</qex> life.</q>
<rj><qau>Bk. of Com. Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men after long emaciating diets, fat, and almost
<qex>new</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Not of ancient extraction, or of a family of ancient
descent; not previously known or famous.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not habituated; not familiar;
unaccustomed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>New</qex> to the plow, unpracticed in the trace.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Fresh from anything; newly come.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>New</qex> from her sickness to that northern air.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>New birth</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Birth</er>.</cd>
-- <mcol><col><b>New Church</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>New Jerusalem
Church</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the church holding the doctrines taught by
<person>Emanuel Swedenborg</person>. See <er>Swedenborgian</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>New heart</b></col> <fld>(Theol.)</fld>, <cd>a heart or
character changed by the power of God, so as to be governed by new and
holy motives.</cd> -- <col><b>New land</b></col>, <cd>land cleared and
cultivated for the first time.</cd> -- <col><b>New light</b></col>.
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Crappie</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>New
moon</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The moon in its first quarter, or when
it first appears after being invisible.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The day
when the new moon is first seen; the first day of the lunar month, which
was a holy day among the Jews.</cd> <au>2 Kings iv. 23.</au> --
<col><b>New Red Sandstone</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>an old name
for the formation immediately above the coal measures or strata, now
divided into the <part>Permian</part> and <part>Trias</part>.</cd> See
<er>Sandstone</er>. -- <col><b>New style</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Style</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>New testament</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Testament</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>New world</b></col>, <cd>the land of
the Western Hemisphere; -- so called because not known to the
inhabitants of the Eastern Hemisphere until recent times.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Novel; recent; fresh; modern. See
<er>Novel</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>New</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: New
<hw>New</hw> <pr>(n⟦umac⟧)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Newly;
recently.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>New</ex> is much used in composition, adverbially,
in the sense of <xex>newly</xex>, <xex>recently</xex>, to qualify other
words, as in <ex>new</ex>-born, <ex>new</ex>-formed, <ex>new</ex>-found,
<ex>new</ex>-mown.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Of new</b></col>, <cd>anew.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>New</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: New
<hw>New</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To make new; to renew.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Newari</ent>⟦br⟧
